8.&nbsp; Moreover, the vast majority of those who have to carry over losses to future years may fully deduct them against capital gains within two or three years.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn40" href="#_ednref40">[40] </a> Thomas L. Hungerford, &ldquo;The Economic Effects of Capital Gains Taxation,&rdquo; Congressional Research Service, June 18, 2010.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn41" href="#_ednref41">[41] </a> Thomas L. Hungerford, &ldquo;An Analysis of the &lsquo;Buffett Rule,&rdquo; Congressional Research Service, October 7, 2011.&nbsp; See section on income taxes below for a discussion of why private saving rates would not likely adjust to counteract the increase in public saving.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn42" href="#_ednref42">[42] </a> Leonard E. Burman, &ldquo;Under the Sheltering Lie,&rdquo; <em>Marketplace </em>commentary, December 20, 2005, <a href="http://www.taxpolicycenter.org/publications/template.cfm?PubID=900918">http://www.taxpolicycenter.org/publications/template.cfm?PubID=900918</a>.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn43" href="#_ednref43">[43] </a> Slemrod, 2003.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn44" href="#_ednref44">[44] </a> Troy Kravitz and Leonard Burman, &ldquo;Capital Gains Tax Rates, Stock Markets, and Growth,&rdquo; Tax Policy Center, November 7, 2005.&nbsp; See also Leonard Burman, &ldquo;Capital Gains Tax Rates and Economic Growth (or not),&rdquo; Forbes blog, March 15, 2012, <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/leonardburman/2012/03/15/capital-gains-tax-rates-and-economic-growth-or-not/">http://www.forbes.com/sites/leonardburman/2012/03/15/capital-gains-tax-rates-and-economic-growth-or-not/</a>. &nbsp;Burman also found no statistically significant effect lagged up to five years: Leonard Burman, <em>The Labyrinth of Capital Gains Tax Policy,</em> Washington, D.C., Brookings Institution, 1999, pp. 81.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn45" href="#_ednref45">[45] </a> Robert J. Barro, &ldquo;Are Government Bonds Net Wealth?,&rdquo; <em>Journal of Political Economy</em>, vol. 82, no. 6. (November-<br />  December, 1974), pp. 1095-1117.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn46" href="#_ednref46">[46] </a>&nbsp; As summarized in D. Andrew Austin, &ldquo;Running Deficits: Positives and Pitfalls,&rdquo; Congressional Research Service, January 2, 2008, referring to Alan J. Auerbach and William G. Gale, &ldquo;Activist Fiscal Policy to Stabilize Economic Activity,&rdquo; working paper, September 29, 2009, <a href="http://elsa.berkeley.edu/~auerbach/activistfiscal.pdf">http://elsa.berkeley.edu/~auerbach/activistfiscal.pdf</a>; Robert E. Hall, &ldquo;By How Much Does GDP Rise If the Government Buys More Output?,&rdquo; Brookings Papers on Economic Activity, Fall 2009, pp. 183-249.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn47" href="#_ednref47">[47] </a> Douglas W. Elmendorf, Director, Congressional Budget Office, <em>The Economic Outlook and Fiscal Policy Choices</em>, Testimony before the Senate Committee on the Budget, September 28, 2010.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn48" href="#_ednref48">[48] </a> This includes owners of small businesses who report zero or negative adjusted gross income (AGI). The Treasury definition of a &ldquo;small business owner&rdquo; includes filers who report active net income from small businesses that equals at least 25 percent of the taxpayer's AGI.&nbsp; &ldquo;Small businesses&rdquo; are identified as pass-through entities that meet certain tests for types and amounts of income reported and deductions claimed (these criteria are intended to exclude filers who do not conduct &ldquo;businesslike&rdquo; activity) and that have both income and deductions of less than $10 million. &nbsp;Matthew Knittel, Susan Nelson, Jason DeBacker, John Kitchen, James Pearce, and Richard Prisinzano, Office of Tax Analysis, Department of the Treasury. &ldquo;Methodology to Identify Small Businesses and Their Owners,&rdquo; Technical Paper 4 August 2011.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn49" href="#_ednref49">[49] </a> See Kevin A. Hassett and Alan D. Viard, &ldquo;The Small Business Tax Hike and the 97% Fallacy,&rdquo; <em>Wall Street Journal</em>, September 3, 2010, <a href="http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052748703959704575454061524326290.html">http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052748703959704575454061524326290.html</a> (&ldquo;According to IRS data, fully 48% of the net income of sole proprietorships, partnerships, and S corporations reported on tax returns went to households with incomes above $200,000 in 2007. That's the number to look at&hellip;&rdquo;).</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn50" href="#_ednref50">[50] </a> The Congressional Research Service has found that &ldquo;current federal tax law contains a number of provisions bestowing preferential treatment on small firms.&rdquo;&nbsp; Gary Geunther, &ldquo;Small Business Tax Benefits: Overview and Economic Rationales,&rdquo; Congressional Research Service, revised September 18, 2007, pp. 3.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn51" href="#_ednref51">[51] </a> Geunther, 2007.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn52" href="#_ednref52">[52] </a> Jane G. Gravelle, &ldquo;Small Business and the Expiration of the 2001 Tax Rate Reductions: Economic Issues,&rdquo; Congressional Research Service, January 6, 2011.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn53" href="#_ednref53">[53] </a> John C. Haltiwanger, Ron S. Jarmin, and Javier Miranda, &ldquo;Who Creates Jobs? Small vs. Large vs. Young,&rdquo; NBER Working Paper No. 16300, issued in August 2010, <a href="http://papers.nber.org/papers/w16300">http://papers.nber.org/papers/w16300</a>.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn54" href="#_ednref54">[54] </a> <em>Ibid, </em>at pp. 30.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn55" href="#_ednref55">[55] </a> Robert Carroll, Douglas Holtz-Eakin, Mark Rider, and Harvey S. Rosen, &ldquo;Entrepreneuers, Income Taxes, and Investment,&rdquo; in ed. Joel B. Slemrod (Cambridge, MA: Harvard University Press, 2000).</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn56" href="#_ednref56">[56] </a> Gravelle, 2011.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn57" href="#_ednref57">[57] </a> See for example, Kevin A. Hassett and Alan D. Viard, &ldquo;The Small Business Tax Hike and the 97% Fallacy,&rdquo; <em>Wall Street Journal</em>, September 3, 2010, <a href="http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052748703959704575454061524326290.html">http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052748703959704575454061524326290.html</a>.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn58" href="#_ednref58">[58] </a> Gravelle, 2011.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn59" href="#_ednref59">[59] </a> Hungerford, 2010.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn60" href="#_ednref60">[60] </a> Gravelle, 2011.&nbsp; CRS also notes that the opportunities for tax avoidance and evasion in self-employment and small business income are greater than by working as an employee:&nbsp; the IRS has estimated that $68 billion of the annual $345 billion gross tax gap for 2001, the most current available estimate, was caused by sole proprietors underreporting their net business income.&nbsp; See Statement of James R. White, &ldquo;Tax Compliance Benefits and Opportunities to Mitigate Costs on Third Parties of Miscellaneous Income Reporting Requirements,&rdquo; Government Accountability Office, November 18, 2010, <a href="http://www.gao.gov/new.items/d11218t.pdf">http://www.gao.gov/new.items/d11218t.pdf</a>.&nbsp; &nbsp;Higher individual income tax rates may encourage some taxpayers to start a business simply to exploit these avoidance and evasion opportunities.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn61" href="#_ednref61">[61] </a> Jane G. Gravelle, &ldquo;Capital Gains Taxes, Innovation and Growth,&rdquo; <em>Congressional Research Service, </em>Updated July 14, 1999.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn62" href="#_ednref62">[62] </a> <em>All</em> capital gains from the sale of certain stock issued in a new corporation were excluded from taxation in 2011 by the Tax Relief Act of 2010.&nbsp; The American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 previously increased the exclusion for such capital gains from 50 percent to 75 percent in 2009 and 2010.&nbsp; The exclusion for such capital gains under current law is 50 percent for 2012 and beyond.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn63" href="#_ednref63">[63] </a> For many types of stock options commonly issued, when the employee (including executive employees) exercises the option, the difference between the option price paid by the employee and the fair market value of the stock is treated as ordinary income to the taxpayer and subject to the ordinary income tax rates, not capital gains tax rates.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn64" href="#_ednref64">[64] </a> Douglas W. Elmendorf, Director, Congressional Budget Office, <em>The Economic Outlook and Fiscal Policy Choices</em>, Testimony before the Senate Committee on the Budget, September 28, 2010, <a href="http://www.cbo.gov/ftpdocs/118xx/doc11874/09-28-EconomicOutlook_Testimony.pdf">http://www.cbo.gov/ftpdocs/118xx/doc11874/09-28-EconomicOutlook_Testimony.pdf</a>.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn65" href="#_ednref65">[65] </a> William Gale and Peter Orszag, &ldquo;Bush Administration Tax Policy:&nbsp; Effects on Long-Term Growth,&rdquo; Tax Notes, October 18, 2004.&nbsp; See also William Gale and Peter Orszag, &ldquo;Budget Deficits, National Saving, and Interest Rates,&rdquo; Brookings Papers on Economic Activity Vol. 2004, No. 2 (2004), pp. 101-187; William Gale and Samara Potter, &ldquo;An Economic Evaluation of the Economic Growth and Tax Relief Reconciliation Act of 2001,&rdquo; National Tax Journal Vol. LV, No. 1, March 2002.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn66" href="#_ednref66">[66] </a> Statement of Leonard E. Burman, Daniel Patrick Moynihan Professor of Public Affairs Maxwell School Syracuse University, Before the Subcommittee on Select Revenue Measures House Ways and Means Committee, Hearing on &ldquo;Taxes and the Budget&rdquo;, March 23, 2010.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn67" href="#_ednref67">[67] </a> &ldquo;The Truth About Taxes and Economic Growth,&rdquo; Interview in <em>Challenge</em>, vol. 46, no. 1, January/February 2003, pp. 5&ndash;14. <a href="http://www.challengemagazine.com/Challenge%20interview%20pdfs/Slemrod.pdf">http://www.challengemagazine.com/Challenge%20interview%20pdfs/Slemrod.pdf</a>.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn68" href="#_ednref68">[68] </a> See: Robert Greenstein, &ldquo;A Framework for Deficit Reduction: Principles and Cautions,&rdquo; Center on Budget and Policy Priorities, March 24, 2011; Hannah Shaw and Chad Stone, &ldquo;Incomes at the Top Rebounded in First Full Year of Recovery, New Analysis of Tax Data Shows Top 1 Percent&rsquo;s Share of Income Starting to Rise Again,&rdquo; Center on Budget and Policy Priorities, March 7, 2012.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn69" href="#_ednref69">[69] </a> For a more detailed discussion of tax expenditure reform to broaden the tax base, see Chuck Marr and Brian Highsmith, &ldquo;Reforming Tax Expenditures Can Reduce Deficits While Making the Tax Code More Efficient and Equitable,&rdquo; Center on Budget and Policy Priorities, April 15, 2011, <a href="http://www.cbpp.org/files/4-15-11tax.pdf">http://www.cbpp.org/files/4-15-11tax.pdf</a>.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn70" href="#_ednref70">[70] </a> Douglas W. Elmendorf, Director, Congressional Budget Office, <em>The Economic Outlook and Fiscal Policy Choices</em>, Testimony before the Senate Committee on the Budget, September 28, 2010. <a href="http://www.cbo.gov/ftpdocs/118xx/doc11874/09-28-EconomicOutlook_Testimony.pdf">http://www.cbo.gov/ftpdocs/118xx/doc11874/09-28-EconomicOutlook_Testimony.pdf</a>.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn71" href="#_ednref71">[71] </a> Id.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn72" href="#_ednref72">[72] </a> See John Creedy, &ldquo;Reflections on the Tax Working Group <em>Report</em>,&rdquo; lecture at the Institute for the Study of Competition and Regulation, Victoria University of Wellington, February 23, 2010; John Creedy, &ldquo;Personal Income Taxation: From Theory to Policy&rdquo;. Australian Economic Review (2009), 42, pp. 495-506.&nbsp;</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn73" href="#_ednref73">[73] </a> Jon Gruber and Emmanuel Saez, &ldquo;The Elasticity of Taxable Income: Evidence and Implications,&rdquo; Journal of Public Economics, 2002, v84 (1, Apr).</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn74" href="#_ednref74">[74] </a> Peter Diamond and Emmanuel Saez, &ldquo;The Case for a Progressive Tax: From Basic Research to Policy Recommendations,&rdquo; CESifo Working Paper No. 3548, August 2011, <a href="http://elsa.berkeley.edu/~saez/diamond-saezJEP11opttax.pdf">http://elsa.berkeley.edu/~saez/diamond-saezJEP11opttax.pdf</a>.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn75" href="#_ednref75">[75] </a> Peter R. Orszag, &ldquo;Marginal Tax Rate Reductions and the Economy: What Would Be the Long-Term Effects of the Bush Tax Cut?,&rdquo; Center on Budget and Policy Priorities, March 16, 2001, <a href="http://www.cbpp.org/cms/index.cfm?fa=view&amp;id=1701">http://www.cbpp.org/cms/index.cfm?fa=view&amp;id=1701</a>.</p>  <p><a title="" name="_edn76" href="#_ednref76">[76] </a> See, for example, Raj Chetty, &ldquo;Is the Taxable Income Elasticity Sufficient to Calculate Deadweight Loss? The Implications of Evasion and Avoidance,&rdquo; <em>American Economic Journal: Economic Policy </em>1(2): 31&ndash;52, 2009.&nbsp;</p>  </div> <P> 
